Teaching with Real Data Notes

Thomas J. Pfaff

Info

Article: Patterns and trends in county-level sex ratios

Authors: Ravan Hawrami and Alanna Williams

Date: Feb 12, 2025

Link: https://aibm.org/research/patterns-and-trends-in-county-level-sex-ratios/

Notes

The data set contains sex ratios, men per 100 women, by county for 2003, 2013, and 2023 with ratios for age groups in 2023. This data set has numerous uses. For inspiration and discussion the map in the article is copied here.

Noted in the article: Counties with incarcerated shares making up more than 5% of their total population have asterisks added to their names. Please exercise caution when analyzing county-level sex ratios by twenty-year age-group, especially for counties with smaller populations.

Uses
  • 1-prop test: Pick your favorite counties and test to see if the proportion is different from 50%. As a bonus students will have to convert the ratios to percentages.
  • 2-prop test: Pick your favorite two counties and test to see if there is a difference in the proportion of men or women. You can also test proportions of two age groups in a county. As a bonus students will have to convert the ratios to percentages.
  • t-test: Test to see if the average ratio in a state by county is different from 100.
  • 2-sample t-test: Pick your favorite two states and test to see if the average ratios by county is different
  • Graphing: Make scatter plots like in the article as well as chloroplast maps. There are others and points can be weighted by population.
  • Wrangling: Find the ratio by state for one idea.
